[[File:Neil Immerman.jpg|thumb|Neil Immerman in 2010.]] '''Neil Immerman''' (24 November 1953, [[Manhasset, New York]]) is an American [[theoretical computer science|theoretical computer scientist]], a professor of computer science at the [[University of Massachusetts Amherst]].<ref name="um-dir">[http://www.cs.umass.edu/faculty/directory/immerman_neil Faculty directory: Neil Immerman], Computer Science Department, [[University of Massachusetts Amherst]], retrieved 2010-01-23.</ref> He is one of the key developers of [[descriptive complexity]], an approach he is currently applying to research in model checking, database theory, and computational complexity theory.
Professor Immerman is an editor of the ''[[SIAM Journal on Computing]]''<ref>[http://www.siam.org/journals/sicomp/board.php Editorial board], ''[[SIAM Journal on Computing]]'', retrieved 2010-01-23.</ref> and of ''[[Logical Methods in Computer Science]]''.<ref>[http://www.lmcs-online.org/ojs/edBoard.php Editorial board], ''[[Logical Methods in Computer Science]]'', retrieved 2010-01-23.</ref> He received B.S. and M.S. degrees from [[Yale University]] in 1974 and his Ph.D. from [[Cornell University]] in 1980 under the supervision of [[Juris Hartmanis]], a [[Turing award]] winner at Cornell.<ref name="um-dir"/><ref>{{mathgenealogy|name=Neil Immerman |id=30442}}.</ref> His book "Descriptive Complexity" appeared in 1999.<ref>Graduate Texts in Computer Science, Springer-Verlag, {{ISBN|978-0-387-98600-5}}.</ref>
Immerman is the winner, jointly with [[Róbert Szelepcsényi]], of the 1995 [[Gödel Prize]] in theoretical computer science for proof of what is known as the [[Immerman–Szelepcsényi theorem]], the result that [[NSPACE|nondeterministic space]] [[complexity class]]es are [[Closure (mathematics)|closed]] under [[Complement (set theory)|complementation]].<ref>[http://sigact.acm.org/prizes/godel/1995.html 1995 Gödel Prize], [[Association for Computing Machinery|ACM]] [[SIGACT]], retrieved 2010-01-23.</ref> Immerman is an [[List of Fellows of the Association for Computing Machinery|ACM Fellow]]<ref>[http://fellows.acm.org/fellow_citation.cfm?id=1758739&srt=all ACM Fellows Award / Neil Immerman], [[Association for Computing Machinery]], retrieved 2010-01-23.</ref> and a [[Guggenheim Fellow]].<ref>[http://www.gf.org/fellows/7088-neil-immerman Neil Immerman] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110604012149/http://www.gf.org/fellows/7088-neil-immerman |date=2011-06-04 }}, John Simon Guggenheim Memorial Foundation, retrieved 2010-01-23.</ref>
